@NikolajBjorner PR #993 changes the CMake build system to be much more similar to what the python/Make system. Once that's merged I suggest creating a brand new build directory and trying a new build.

One thing you didn't mention is how you configuring the old build system. If you were using `--optimize` configure flag from the python/Makefile build system then you can now do the same thing with the CMake build system by passing `-DLINK_TIME_OPTIMIZATION=TRUE` to the cmake command when configuring.

Note I have very low confidence in using `LINK_TIME_OPTIMIZATION` with gcc/clang so I don't advise using it with those compilers yet. When I tried I got a bunch of warnings about one-definition rule violations so there's like some latent bugs in Z3 that need to be fixed.

@rhelmot It seems to works great, I have encounter another bug though related to errno:
```
#include <unistd.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <errno.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

int main()
{
    int filedesc = open("", O_WRONLY | O_APPEND);
    if(filedesc < 0) {
        printf("something went wrong with open()! %s\n", strerror(errno));
        return 1;
    }

    return 0;
}
```
If I run the binary on x86 elf on ubuntu it returns (as expected):
`something went wrong with open()! No such file or directory`
however if I run it with angr exploration it seems errno value is 0.

this is the main function:
![open_empty_file_errno](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7024240/41899724-dd07b806-7935-11e8-8f8e-019010eee316.PNG)

there is implementation of the function: `__errno_location` in here: [link](https://github.com/angr/angr/blob/master/angr/procedures/glibc/__errno_location.py)

but it seems we create the variable of errno only after call to `__errno_location` which is already after open has been running, therefore not saving the error code returned.

I've attached the example code binary (ARM ELF 32Bit) and the example exploration:
[link to the file](https://ufile.io/2bqda)

the simple exploration (if you do steps you will see after the call to `__errno_location` r0 register point to the heap we allocated for errno and the value in that memory is 0):
```
import angr
p = angr.Project(r"open_empty_string", load_options={"auto_load_libs": False})
state = p.factory.call_state(addr=0x10588) # main function
simgr = p.factory.simulation_manager(state)
simgr.step(); simgr.step(); simgr.step(); simgr.step(); simgr.step(); simgr.step(); simgr.step(); simgr.active # we should stop at: 0x105B4
print simgr.active[0].regs.r0
print simgr.active[0].memory.load(simgr.active[0].regs.r0) # this is errno value shows 0
```

I've also tried to run from the _start function since I though it might be the one initializing the errno variable (calling `__errno_location`?) but it doesn't have any effect.

